Post.create!([
  {title: "Spring Crops are in swing", body: "So as of this week, tomato’s have their flowers, this means with pollination and heat fruit is so to follow, same with zucchini plants, small squash already forming. Cukes are climbing on their trellis also blooming, small cucumbers should appear any day.\r\nRow crops are well up, Spinach, and kale both colder weather crops are up and in use, lettuce is in full swing and we are harvesting as fast as we can eat it. Once the real heat sets in lettuce fades. Snap Peas also ready to pick a few, they will carry on for a while. These cool nights are great for row crops and peas, but the dukes and tomatoes will need the heat to jump up. Potato beds are covered with growth, depending on the type this will die down as an indication that you can dig the tubers up, most let them stay in a bit longer to increase the size. Just heap fresh mulch or compost on the bed as they like it cool and shady. Other than that,  all herbs are up and big enough to pick and dry, Basil, Rosemary, Thyme, Oregano, and Peppermint all doing well.\r\nThe Hollyhocks are in bloom as well, I’ll send pictures.\r\nGood luck to all!   \r\n-Kevin", user_id: 11},
  {title: "All season succulents", body: "The succulents are doing really great in the full sun my west facing window receives. Today I began propagating new succulents by plucking off a few of the bottom leaves of my current plants, laying them in some potting mix, and spraying them with water. I also planted two gladiolus bulbs in separate pots. When they begin to sprout, I’ll have to transfer them to a much larger pot so they can grow nice and tall!", user_id: 12},
  {title: "Growing is sweet in the Texas heat", body: "I'm new to gardening and decided to start with some hardy sun-loving plants. I chose Ice Plant, cactus, and other succulent type plants because I heard they are harder to kill. I don't have much of a green thumb yet, but I hope to change that with experience! I was wondering if anyone had any advice on keeping rabbits out of your yards? I am missing a new plant every morning because of these darn things. \r\nWell wishes to all!", user_id: 14},
  {title: "Four score and seven seeds ago...", body: "I've planted my first row of banana peppers and I can not tell a lie, I have quite the green thumb! The garden is looking lush as all the cold weather crops are coming in and making way for the later summer harvest. It looks like this fall will be a bountiful season!", user_id: 16}
